   But wait, what if the second program outputs 7 in a context where the input had nothing to do with 5's? This is a transformation of the original programs. However, the original chain would have: Program1: output x
        Program2: input x, output y
        Program3: input y (as a string) and then try to split it into three integers -> it will fail because there is only one integer. So the original chain would crash on the third program.

And it maintains the chain: 
        the output of the first program (x) is used by the second program to compute y.
        the output of the second program (y) is used by the third program to decide the output. And only the first block reads input. And there are no intermediate I/O. And the final output is only at the end. We hope this is what the problem intended. Let's do it. Steps in C:

   Step1: read n and k.
   Step2: read n integers into an array. Step3: sort the array (only the first k elements matter) and sum the first k.
   Step4: compute y = 0;
          for i from 1 to x (which is the sum from step3) {
              term = i * (x / i) * (x / i + 1) / 2;
              y += term;
          }
   Step5: if (y == 7) then printf("YES\n"); else printf("NO\n");

